ATTENTION:
Families and students of Lee County Schools, we are excited to announce that the USDA just approved us to serve ALL STUDENTS FOR FREE, beginning this MONDAY, September 7th!

That means ALL!

No matter what your status is, i.e. paid and reduced, student meals will ALL be FREE for BREAKFAST AND LUNCH!! This will be in effect until December 31st, 2020, or until USDA says otherwise.

We know some parents have received free/reduced lunch applications the last few days, please continue to fill those out and send them back to school as we need those for our Title I status for our school system and since your child will go to their regular approved status beginning January 2021.

Vaya aquí para la versión en español del anuncio: https://bit.ly/anunciodecomidasgratisenespañol

post_text:
After receiving further guidance from ALSDE we will not require the students be in the vehicles for the pickup of food. However, the parent will be required to have the child’s lunch card with them in order to pick up food without the child present. If your child does not have a lunch card, please, contact your school lunchroom manager via the school office before Monday.

Pickup times are every Monday from 8:00-10:00am CST for Pre-K – 8th grade and 10:00am-12:00pm CST for 9th – 12th grade. The meals must still be picked up at the school that each child attends. For further instruction and information, please, visit the Child Nutrition (under the Departments tab) section of our website at www.lee.k12.al.us

Thank you!

post_text: In response to COVID-19, we recently surveyed our stakeholders regarding the return to school in August 2020. Many of the respondents indicated a desire for an online learning option rather than returning to an adjusted traditional school setting. As a result of your feedback, Lee County Schools will be offering access to virtual learning for all grades this school year in addition to the planned re-opening of schools. A brief description of the virtual learning plan can be found at www.lee.k12.al.us or you may call your local school for more information.

post_text:
An unfortunate side effect of canceling classes due to the pending public health crisis is that some of our food-insecure families lose out on the school lunches that help provide the nourishment students need. In an effort to help with this, there are some organizations offering assistance to those families in need. The Hudson Family Foundation (@HudsonFamilyFdn) has coordinated with Philadelphia Baptist Church in Smiths Station to provide Emergency Food Assistance to Lee County Families who need it. Food will be distributed on Monday, March 23rd. Please follow this link to sign up to receive help if you need it http://bit.ly/3b9fsTp
We will also post an announcement from Lee County EMA with more Food Assistance in a separate post. Thank you and stay safe.

post_text:
Update from Lee County Schools for March 16, 2020

1. We continue to wish everyone health and safety. Stay vigilant in pursuing best practices to take care of yourself and your family.
2. Thank you to all for your efforts to navigate through these unprecedented times.
3.General Announcements

a) Any instructional assignments or resources provided while school is closed are solely optional learning opportunities. No assignment is for required completion during the school. closure.

b) If your student has medication located at school that you need during the school closure, it may be picked up Tuesday, March 17 or Wednesday, March 18 between the hours of 9AM to 3PM CDT. A parent must sign for the medication at the time of retrieval. Call your school for specific pick up procedures.

Thank you. We will continue to provide updates as relevant information becomes available.

post_text: Teachers and staff from around our region have been participating in SAMUEL training at our Central Office provided by the Alabama State Department of Education the last two days. As always, it is our pleasure to host these trainings. SAMUEL, School Assistance Meetings for Understanding English Learners, trainings are offered by the ALSDE Federal Programs Department EL team. This professional development opportunity is provided for educational personnel, to disseminate updated information concerning effective educational interaction with EL students and their families. Administrators, EL Coaches/Teachers, EL Paraprofessionals, Classroom Teachers, and other personnel are generally invited to attend these meetings.

post_text: Today is the third day of National School Counseling Week. Did you know that your attitude can help you take on the challenges and obstacles you face in your daily life? We all know people who are grumpy. Or negative. Or ungrateful. They find it easier to complain about their obstacles than to work through them. But as Michael Jordan once said, “Obstacles don’t have to stop you. If you run into a wall, don’t turn around and give up. Figure out how to climb it, go through it or work around it.” Babe Ruth, one of the greatest baseball players ever, had a similar attitude. “Every strike,” he said, “brings me closer to the next home run.” Take a moment to think about your attitude. Do you approach things positively or negatively? Do you reach out to others for support? Reach out to your school counselor. Feel free to stop by their office anytime.

post_text: Today is the second day of National School Counseling Week. Our focus for the week is “Resilience,” the inner strength that helps you overcome the challenges and obstacles you have in life to help you become a better human. One of our couselors’ goals is to help you learn new skills to help you succeed. Facing your fears is one of those skills, and it’s one we all have to practice, too. Determination, self-confidence, and bravery – all of which are characteristics of resilience – can be hard. But being brave, determined and self-confident starts with standing up to fear. If you ever want to chat about your fears and ways to overcome them, feel free to stop by and talk to your school counselor. They are here to help!

post_text: Doodle for Google is an annual contest open to students in grades K-12. Students are invited to create their own Google Doodle for the chance to have it featured on Google.com, as well as win some great scholarships and tech packages for their schools. The contest is open for entries until March 13, 2020, 8:00pm Pacific Time. Use your imagination to create a Google Doodle based on what kindness means to you. You can find more information here: https://doodles.google.com/d4g/how-it-works/

post_text: In partnership with HNH Immunizations (Health Heroes), it is our pleasure to offer on-site flu vaccinations to students this year on October 28. Flu clinics will be offered at each school location during school hours. Health Heroes clinics are completely voluntary and are offered to all students with parental consent age 4 and up. Your school nurse is distributing permission forms which must be completed for your child to receive the vaccine. Call your school nurse for any questions or if you need another permission form.

post_text: It was an exciting day for our faculty, coaches, and student athletes at Smiths Station Junior High! They were honored to have State Representatives Chris Blackshear and Debbie Wood, along with State Senator Randy Price, on campus this morning as they presented the school with a grant check totaling $16,500.00 to be used towards giving the weight room a complete makeover. These funds have been donated to purchase new strength and conditioning equipment for all of Smiths Junior High’s student athletes. Huge thanks to our local state leaders for their contributions and for their commitment to serving our schools and students.

post_text: The Alabama Leaders in Educational Technology awards a $10,000 college scholarship each spring. The scholarship is named for the late Debbie Rice, a long time leader in the organization who served as the Technology Director for Auburn City Schools until 2014. Applications for the 2020 ALET Debbie Rice Memorial Scholarship are now being taken. All applications must be postmarked by November 2, 2019 and must be mailed to their Montgomery address. You can find more information and the application at https://go-alet.org/scholarship/

Lee County Schools
April 10, 2019 at 7:52 PM ·

Reminder: If you are the parent of a child in one of our elementary schools and you are interested in your child attending our summer STEM academy, PLTW, then please apply at this link: https://goo.gl/forms/QY16v5TF2W1j9iGt2 If you would like to hear more about the program, you can listen here: https://goo.gl/vYsRgJ

Please contact your child's school for details such as dates and other questions.

post_text: Mend is establishing support groups for survivors of the March 3rd Tornadoes. They will be meeting at Providence Baptist Church on 04/29/19 from 5:30-7:00 PM. Counselors and other specialists will be on hand to help. #BeauregardStrong #LeeCountyStrong
